        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The F statistic is used to compare in-group variances to between-group\nvariances. Calculating the distribution depends on the sampling, and\nso it is a function of the respective degrees of freedom in the\nproblem.  The variable "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "dfnum"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is the number of samples minus one, the\nbetween-groups degrees of freedom, while "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "dfden"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is the within-groups\ndegrees of freedom, the sum of the number of samples in each group\nminus the number of groups."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "raw_kind": "footnote",
            "raw_text": "1\n\nGlantz, Stanton A. \"Primer of Biostatistics.\", McGraw-Hill,\nFifth Edition, 2002.",
            "type": "raw_block"
          },
          {
            "raw_kind": "footnote",
            "raw_text": "2\n\nWikipedia, \"F-distribution\",\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-distribution",
            "type": "raw_block"
          }
        ],
        "title": "References"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "An example from Glantz[1], pp 47-40:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Two groups, children of diabetics (25 people) and children from people\nwithout diabetes (25 controls). Fasting blood glucose was measured,\ncase group had a mean value of 86.1, controls had a mean value of\n82.2. Standard deviations were 2.09 and 2.49 respectively. Are these\ndata consistent with the null hypothesis that the parents diabetic\nstatus does not affect their children's blood glucose levels?\nCalculating the F statistic from the data gives a value of 36.01."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Draw samples from the distribution:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "dfnum = 1. # between group degrees of freedom"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "dfden = 48. # within groups degrees of freedom"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "s = fnp.random.f(dfnum, dfden, 1000)"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The lower bound for the top 1% of the samples is :"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "fnp.sort(s)[-10]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "7.61988120985 # random"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "So there is about a 1% chance that the F statistic will exceed 7.62,\nthe measured value is 36, so the null hypothesis is rejected at the 1%\nlevel."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
